[h4 id=Bios_3 
	" BIOS
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Launch the config and you'll see this (maybe familiar) POST screen:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/post.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Hit DEL on this screen before it finishes to enter the setup menu.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/standard-cmos-setup.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Select Standard CMOS Setup and press Enter. Leave Primary Master and Slave at Auto, and select the Type for Secondary Master and Slave and use PgUp to set them to None. Select Drive A and use PgUp/PgDown to set it to 2.88M, 3.5 in., and then select Drive B and set it to 1.2M, 5.25 in.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/drive-b.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Press Esc to back out to the setup menu. Select BIOS Features Setup and press Enter. Go down to Boot Sequence and use PgUp to set it to CDROM, A, C. Remember how to do this - you will have to change it to boot to C later.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/boot-sequence.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Press Esc to back out to the setup menu and then press F10 to save & exit setup. Press Y and then Enter to save to CMOS and exit. The PC will restart looking for bootable media: proceed to the 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=FreeDOS Installation section|href=/EmulatorResources/PCem/DOS#FreedosInstallation)
	".
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h2 id=FreedosInstallation 
	" FreeDOS installation
	$LF
]h2
[h3 id=Media 
	" Media
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"These configs will have FreeDOS 1.2 installed on them. For these configs, you will need the Legacy installer. You can get everything on the 
	[a href=https://www.ibiblio.org/pub/micro/pc-stuff/freedos/files/distributions/1.2/official/ rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"FreeDOS website
	]a
	". 
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Right-click on the PCem window and use CD-ROM -> Load image to load FD12LGCY.iso (
	[code 
		"md5: a55750577b4c3b88dba489df4f929f88
	]code
	"). If your system is older and doesn't support booting from CD (like the 80s setups), you'll also need to download FD12FLOPPY.zip (
	[code 
		"md5: 6c3077be89db961a883b1587385aa65e
	]code
	") and mount FLOPPY.img using Disc -> Change drive A. Restart the system when everything is mounted.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Installation 
	" Installation
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"You will get some messages about illegal partitions - this is normal, the drive hasn't been formatted yet. Partitioning and formatting is built in to the FreeDOS installer to make this as easy as possible. On the first couple screens, choose English and choose Yes to continue with the installation. You will get a message saying drive C: is not partitioned yet, choose Yes to continue. Once the partitioning is complete, reboot the system with System -> Hard Reset (PCem doesn't like the installer's restarts for some reason).
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Once the CD boots up again (you may have to mount it again), pick English again and Yes to continue the installation. The installer will ask you if you want to format, choose Yes. The drive will be formatted and you should see a screen like this:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/formatting.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Once it finishes loading, pick US English as the keyboard layout. When it asks what FreeDOS packages to install, pick Base packages only.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/base-packages-only.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Choose Yes on the next screen to install. Installation will take a few minutes. When it's done, reboot with System -> Hard reset again.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=BootOrder 
	" Boot order
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"The hard drive is now bootable, so you should change the boot order so that it's the first option. When the system restarts, enter the BIOS again. How you do this will depend on the chipset you're using.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=Late80s_2 
	" Late 80s
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"The boot order can't be changed, just eject the floppy disk.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=Early90s_2 
	" Early 90s
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Hit F1 at POST and go to Boot Options. Put the list in the following order: Hard Disk, CD-ROM, Floppy, Disabled. Press F10 to save and exit.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=Late90s_2 
	" Late 90s
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Hit DEL at POST and go to BIOS Features Setup. Set Boot Sequence to C, CDROM, A. Press Esc, then F10, then Y, then Enter.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=SetBlaster 
	" Set blaster
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"The last thing to do is set the proper Sound Blaster variables. To do this, you will have to edit AUTOEXEC.BAT.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"When you boot the config, it will now take you to a 
	[code 
		"C:>
	]code
	" prompt. Type 
	[code 
		"edit AUTOEXEC.BAT
	]code
	" into the prompt and hit enter. You should see this:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/configurations/set-blaster.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Note the line that starts with 
	[code 
		"SET BLASTER
	]code
	" - this is the one you will be changing. What you change it to depends on the type of Sound Blaster you picked - look 
	[a href=https://retronn.de/imports/soundblaster_config_guide.html rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"here
	]a
	" for more info. The IRQ is always 7, the DMA is always 1, the high DMA is always 5, and the I/O port was set in the Sound tab when the config was made. For the premade configs, replace this line with one of the following:
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=Late80s_3 
	" Late 80s
	$LF
]h4
[pre 
	"SET BLASTER=A220 I7 D1 T4
	$LF
]pre
[h4 id=Early90sAndLate90s 
	" Early 90s and Late 90s
	$LF
]h4
[pre 
	"SET BLASTER=A220 I7 D1 H5 P330 T6
	$LF
]pre
[div class=p 
	"Once this line is changed, in the editor pick File -> Save and then File -> Exit. The config should now be ready to use!
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Note that you will not have the same file hashes as the ones we provide unless you run the verification movie. The times and dates stored in the files will be different.
	$LF
]div
[hr 
]hr
[h2 id=CustomInstallation 
	" Custom installation
	$LF
]h2
[div class=p 
	"If you need to format the hard drive yourself and install something else, put in your boot disk and restart PCem.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"After you boot PCem with the boot disk in the floppy drive, eventually you'll be met with an 
	[code 
		"A:>
	]code
	" prompt.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/prompt.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Any good boot disk will have FDISK and FORMAT on it.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Partitioning 
	" Partitioning
	$LF
]h3
[ul 
	[li 
		" Type 
		[code 
			"fdisk
		]code
		" into the prompt and hit Enter.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Say yes to large disk support.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Choose option 1 on the next menu to create a DOS partition
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Pick option 1 again to make a primary DOS partition.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Say yes to using the maximum available space and making it the active partition.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"If all goes well, you should see a screen like this:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/drive-partitioning.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"The drive is now partitioned. Escape out of FDISK and restart PCem like it wants you to.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Formatting 
	" Formatting
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Now it's time to format.
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Let the system boot up again and get to the 
		[code 
			"A:>
		]code
		" prompt.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Type 
		[br 
		]br
		" 
		[code 
			"  format c:
		]code
		" 
		[br 
		]br
		" and press Enter.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" You'll get a warning that all data will be lost, but there is no data anyway, so say yes.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Give the volume a name (or leave it blank) and hit Enter.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"You should see a screen like this once it's finished:
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[img class=embed mw-100 src=https://files.tasvideos.org/common/Wiki/pcem/dos/drive-formatting.png 
	]img
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"The hard drive is now ready to be used. After you install your game and get libTAS set up, you should be ready to start TASing at this point.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Note 
	" Note
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"You can press F8 after the POST screen to step through each line in 
	[code 
		"fdconfig.sys
	]code
	" and 
	[code 
		"autoexec.bat
	]code
	". Only do this if you know what you're doing, but you can use this to skip loading things like emm386, ctmouse, and/or the CD drivers.
]div
